In my opinion, handling observables this way will make it difficult to maintain the code in the long run. If you have multiple observables to subscribe to, you will also have to handle their subscription etc..

So, for this specific case, here&#39;s how I&#39;d solve it:
```typescript
const source = of(1, 2, 3);

const subscription = source
  .pipe(
    /**
     * `Pause` the main observable
     * Won&#39;t to get the next emitted value until this inner subscription is done
     */
    concatMap(v =&gt; {
      // The if block
      if (v === 2) {
        // Getting some data from the condition
        return of(&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;c&#39;);
      }

      return of(&#39;default value&#39;);
    }),
  )
  .subscribe(v =&gt; console.log(&#39;value received!&#39;, v))
```

`concatMap` is one of the [high order operators](https://blog.angular-university.io/rxjs-higher-order-mapping/).

It will also return an observable, whose subscription will **internally** be handled by `concatMap`.

[StackBlitz](https://stackblitz.com/edit/rxjs-bqbfow?devtoolsheight=60).

